    "science_hero": {
      "type": "shower-science-hero",
      "settings": {
        "badge": "RESEARCH-BACKED SCIENCE",
        "title_prefix": "The Biology Behind Why",
        "title_accent": "Your Water Matters More Now",
        "description": "The same hormonal changes causing your hair and skin to shift also make you more vulnerable to contaminants in your shower water. Here's the science — no marketing, no fluff, just the research."
      }
    },
    "science_compounding": {
      "type": "shower-science-compounding",
      "settings": {
        "heading": "THE CORE INSIGHT",
        "title": "The Compounding Effect: 1 + 1 = 3",
        "description": "Hormonal changes and unfiltered water aren't two separate problems. They compound each other, creating accelerated damage that neither would cause alone.",
        "card1_title": "Less Oil Produced",
        "card1_desc": "Estrogen decline reduces sebum production. Your scalp and skin make fewer protective oils.",
        "card2_title": "Remaining Oil Stripped",
        "card2_desc": "Chlorine oxidizes and strips what little natural oil your body still produces, leaving nothing.",
        "card3_title": "Exponential Dryness",
        "card3_desc": "Zero protective oil layer = extreme vulnerability. Products can't absorb. Follicles are exposed.",
        "expand_title": "Deep Dive: How Estrogen Loss + Chlorine Create a Vicious Cycle",
        "p1": "Estrogen directly regulates sebum production through insulin-like growth factor receptors on sebocytes (oil-producing cells). As estrogen levels decline during perimenopause and menopause, sebum output can drop significantly — leaving your skin and scalp with less of its natural protective oil layer.",
        "p2": "Chlorine is a powerful oxidant. Its entire purpose in municipal water is to kill living organisms by oxidizing their cell walls. When it contacts your skin and hair, it does the same thing to your natural oils — breaking down the lipid barrier that keeps moisture in and irritants out.",
        "p3_title": "At 25, this isn't a major problem.",
        "p3": "Young skin produces abundant sebum and can replenish its oil layer quickly after a chlorinated shower. The damage is temporary.",
        "p4_title": "At 50, it's a completely different situation.",
        "p4": "Your body is producing less oil AND chlorine is stripping what remains. There isn't enough sebum to rebuild the barrier between showers. Each shower compounds the deficit. This is why dryness, itching, and irritation accelerate — it's not just aging. It's aging plus daily chemical exposure on a body that can no longer compensate.",
        "citation": "Sources: Ashcroft et al., 1997 (estrogen/sebocyte regulation) · Brincat et al., 1987 (collagen/estrogen correlation) · Aquasana skin disorder research",
        "tip_number": "2×",
        "tip_title": "The compounding factor:",
        "tip_text": "A woman at 50 with unfiltered water faces roughly double the effective moisture loss from each shower compared to her 25-year-old self — not because the water got worse, but because her body's ability to recover from it decreased."
      }
    },
